Truong Huy San is a Vietnamese activist and writer known for criticizing government policies and advocating for human rights and democracy. He has faced harassment, surveillance, and imprisonment because of his outspoken views. In countries with strict censorship and monitoring, activists risk their safety and freedom when communicating openly.

Protecting data and messages helps shield activists from government spying, making it harder for authorities to track their activities or intercept sensitive information. Using secure, offline-encrypted communication tools reduces the risk of surveillance and retaliation. Keywords to explore include digital security, online censorship, encrypted messaging, privacy protection, and activist safety.